2. passuum: not by our reckoning; pace with us is the same as step, the space included between the feet in walking. The Roman pace was double ours, the space passed over between the footfalls of the same foot. Yet the Roman mile was somewhat shorter than ours.

3. tumultu: used by the Romans particularly of a rebellion or insurrection right at home, and consequently dangerous. Hence it is chosen here to lay stress upon the suddenness and danger of this bellum.

6. hemerodromoe: Greek noun of second declens. (G. 43, d; H. 54, note 1). Keep the same word in English. The perform- ances of some of these runners were most extraordinary. Alter the battle of Plataea, one of them ran from the battlefield to Delphi and back (perhaps 112 miles altogether) in one day. In the present instance Phidippus reached Sparta (more than 125 miles distant) on the second day.
